The most commonly used linux commands are explained below. 

 1.pwd: pwd is a Linux / Unix command which prints the current working directory. pwd stands for Print Working Directory.
 2.vi: The vi editor (short for visual editor) is a screen editor which is available on almost all Unix systems.
   vi has no menus but instead uses combinations of keystrokes in order to accomplish commands.
 3.touch: touch is a standard Unix command-line interface program which is used to update the access date
          and / or modification date of a file or directory.
 4.mkdir: The mkdir command is is used to create new directories.
 5.rm:    The rm command removes each specified file. By default, it does not remove directories.
 6.ls:    The ls command is a Linux shell command that lists directory contents of files and directories.
 7.echo:  The echo Command. echo is a built-in command in the bash and C shells that writes its arguments to standard output.
 8.cat:   The cat command concatenate files and print on the standard output
 9.who:   Who command is a tool for showing who is currently logged in at the time. This tool can also show last reboot and current run-level information.
10.cd:    The cd command, which stands for "change directory", changes the shell's current working directory.
11.date:  The date command prints or set the system date and time
12.cal:   The cal displays a calendar
13.mv:    The mv command is used to move or rename files
14.cp:    The cp command is used to make copies of files and directories.
15.which: The which command is a Unix command used to identify the location of executables.
